It&#x27;s not surprising, and it is not peculiar to FNV-1a. Most of these hashes will exhibit this same behavior.<p>Since the hash iterates over the characters in the string, once you find two colliding strings S and T, if you append any other string to both S and T, the hashes of S&#x27; and T&#x27; will also be identical. Try it yourself:<p><pre><code>    #include <stdio.h>
    #include &quot;hash_32a.c&quot;
    int main(int argc, char* argv[])
    {
        const char* s[] = {
            &quot;altarage&quot;,
            &quot;zinke&quot;,
            &quot;altarage_foo&quot;,
            &quot;zinke_foo&quot;,
            &quot;altarage_xyzzy&quot;,
            &quot;zinke_xyzzy&quot;
        };
        int i;
        for (i = 0; i < sizeof s / sizeof (char*); ++i)
        {
            Fnv32_t x = fnv_32a_str(s[i], FNV1_32A_INIT);
            printf(&quot;%s: %08x
&quot;, s[i], x);
        }
    }


    $ ./test_fnv1a
    altarage:       e460d8b6
    zinke:          e460d8b6
    altarage_foo:   3d8619c5
    zinke_foo:      3d8619c5
    altarage_xyzzy: 2a6373cf
    zinke_xyzzy:    2a6373cf</code></pre>
